  </div>
  
  <div class="views-field-teaser">
                <div class="field-content"><p><a href="http://unfccc.int/2860.php">The Cancun Agreements</a> have been <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/cwire/2010/12/13/13climatewire-a-near-consensus-decision-keeps-un-climate-p-77618.html">widely praised</a> as a step forward for the international climate negotiating process to address climate change. In the run-up to this year‚Äôs meeting in Cancun there was a lot of <a href="http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/12/10/AR2010121002876.html">concern</a> about how the relationship between the United States and China would play out in the negotiations, and whether the competing interests of the world‚Äôs two largest emitters would be an impediment to progress. However, in these negotiations, there were improved relations&#8211; both in tone and engagement&#8211; between the United States and China.</p></div>
  </div>
  </div>
